Your MongoDB is connected, but it's returning an empty array ([]) because there are no records in your database yet.
âœ… How to Check and Insert Data in MongoDB Atlas
Step 1: Open MongoDB Atlas and Check Your Collection

    Go to MongoDB Atlas.
    Click on your Cluster (e.g., Cluster0).
    Go to Collections under Database section.
    Check if a collection named records exists.
        If the records collection is empty, you need to insert some test data.

Step 2: Manually Insert Test Data

Option 1: Insert Data via MongoDB Atlas UI

    Go to Database > Browse Collections > Select records collection`.
    Click "Insert Document" and add:

    {
      "name": "Test Record 1",
      "position": "Developer",
      "level": "Senior"
    }

    Click Insert and refresh your frontend.

Option 2: Insert Data via a POST Request (API Call) If you already have the POST /record route in your backend, you can manually add a new record using Postman or cURL.

ðŸ‘‰ Use Postman or Run this in Terminal:

curl -X POST http://localhost:5050/record \
     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
     -d '{"name": "Test Record", "position": "Engineer", "level": "Junior"}'

Step 3: Restart Server & Refresh Frontend

    Restart the server (Ctrl + C, then node server.js).
    Go to your frontend and refresh the page (F5).
    Check if records appear in the browser console.

